The praises of Alexander , transmitted by a succession of poets and historians , had kindled a dangerous emulation in the mind of Trajan . 
Yet the success of Trajan , however transient , was rapid and specious . 
The degenerate Parthians , broken by intestine discord , fled before his arms . 
He descended the River Tigris in triumph , from the mountains of Armenia to the Persian Gulf . 
He enjoyed the honor of being the first , as he was the last , of the Roman generals , who ever navigated that remote sea . 
His fleets ravaged the coast of Arabia and Trajan vainly flattered himself that he was approaching towards the confines of India . 
Every day the astonished senate received the intelligence of new names and new nations , that acknowledged his sway . 
Trajan's sentiments are represented in a very just and lively manner in the Caesars of Julian . 
Eutropius and Sextus Rufus have endeavored to perpetuate the illusion . 
See a very sensible dissertation of M. Freret in the Academie des Inscriptions , tom . 
