M. Both Niger and Albinus were discovered and put to death in their flight from the field of battle . 
Their fate excited neither surprise nor compassion . 
But his unforgiving temper , stimulated by avarice , indulged a spirit of revenge , where there was no room for apprehension . 
Till the final decision of the war , the cruelty of Severus was , in some measure , restrained by the uncertainty of the event , and his pretended reverence for the senate . 
The head of Albinus , accompanied with a menacing letter , announced to the Romans that he was resolved to spare none of the adherents of his unfortunate competitors . 
He was irritated by the just auspicion that he had never possessed the affections of the senate , and he concealed his old malevolence under the recent discovery of some treasonable correspondences . 
