Robertson's Charles V. Hume's Political Essays . 
Note It is a wise observation of Malthus , that these nations were not populous in proportion to the land they occupied , but to the food they produced . 
They were prolific from their pure morals and constitutions , but their institutions were not calculated to produce food for those whom they brought into being . 
A warlike nation like the Germans , without either cities , letters , arts , or money , found some compensation for this savage state in the enjoyment of liberty . 
Their poverty secured their freedom , since our desires and our possessions are the strongest fetters of despotism . 
