Posterity admires , and will long admire , the awful remains of the amphitheatre of Titus , which so well deserved the epithet of Colossal . 
The outside of the edifice was encrusted with marble , and decorated with statues . 
Nothing was omitted , which , in any respect , could be subservient to the convenience and pleasure of the spectators . 
They were protected from the sun and rain by an ample canopy , occasionally drawn over their heads . 
The air was continally refreshed by the playing of fountains , and profusely impregnated by the grateful scent of aromatics . 
In the centre of the edifice , the arena , or stage , was strewed with the finest sand , and successively assumed the most different forms . 
At one moment it seemed to rise out of the earth , like the garden of the Hesperides , and was afterwards broken into the rocks and caverns of Thrace . 
