Chapter XIII Reign Of Diocletian And This Three Associates . 
When the Roman princes had lost sight of the senate and of their ancient capital , they easily forgot the origin and nature of their legal power . 
The civil offices of consul , of proconsul , of censor , and of tribune , by the union of which it had been formed , betrayed to the people its republican extraction . 
The name of Emperor , which was at first of a military nature , was associated with another of a more servile kind . 
Viewing it in that odious light , it had been rejected with abhorrence by the first Caesars . 
But the sentiments of the East were very different from those of the West . 
Even the attributes , or at least the titles , of the Divinity , were usurped by Diocletian and Maximian , who transmitted them to a succession of Christian emperors . 
