It is the undoubted right of every society to exclude from its communion and benefits such among its members as reject or violate those regulations which have been established by general consent . 
The consequences of excommunication were of a temporal as well as a spiritual nature . 
The Christian against whom it was pronounced , was deprived of any part in the oblations of the faithful . 
The situation of these unfortunate exiles was in itself very painful and melancholy but , as it usually happens , their apprehensions far exceeded their sufferings . 
With regard to the treatment of these penitents , two opposite opinions , the one of justice , the other of mercy , divided the primitive church . 
A milder sentiment was embraced in practice as well as in theory , by the purest and most respectable of the Christian churches . 
According to the circumstances or the number of the guilty , the exercise of the Christian discipline was varied by the discretion of the bishops . 
Among these we may distinguish the inexpiable guilt of calumniating a bishop , a presbyter , or even a deacon . 
The Montanists and the Novatians , who adhered to this opinion with the greatest rigor and obstinacy , found themselves at last in the number of excommunicated heretics . 
